  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "lesson-2",
      "name": "Pre-Assessment",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": true,
      "has_lesson_plan": false,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-2",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-1",
      "name": "Talking to Machines",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I use AI effectively?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how AI generates responses by recognizing patterns and predicting likely outcomes. Through a “Yes, and…” game, they simulate AI’s response-building process. They experiment using text and images to craft effective prompts using AI Chat levels. By the end, they understand how AI processes information and how to use strategic prompting for better results.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use AI effectively?**\n\nExplore how AI predicts responses and practice crafting better prompts to get more useful AI-generated answers."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-1",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-4",
      "name": "Beyond Words",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How does AI process different types of media?**\n\n In this lesson, students explore how multimodal AI models process and interpret different types of media by comparing AI-generated responses to text-only vs text and image inputs. Through hands-on activities and discussions, they analyze AI’s capabilities, limitations, and ethical considerations, reinforcing their understanding of effective prompting and privacy risks in AI applications.",
        "student_overview": "**How does AI process different types of media?**\n\nIn this lesson, explore how multimodal AI models interpret different types of media by comparing responses to text-only vs. text and image inputs. Through hands-on activities and discussions, discover what AI can and can’t do, how to ask better questions, and why privacy matters when using AI."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-4",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-5",
      "name": "The AI's Brain",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do AI models learn?**\n\nIn this lesson, students uncover how large language models (LLMs) are trained, how they use neural networks to predict text, and how context shapes AI responses. Through an unplugged neural network activity, students simulate how AI generates predictions with and without context. They explore how LLMs rely on pattern recognition, probability, and human feedback to improve over time. Finally, students experiment with zero-shot, one-shot, and multi-shot prompting to see how different levels of input impact AI’s output.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Unplugged Neural Networks Activity Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do AI models learn?**\n\nIn this lesson, explore how AI learns to predict responses and how context shapes its answers. Try real-world prompts and see how giving more detail helps AI respond more clearly."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-5",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-6",
      "name": "Smart or Just Predictable?",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Where does AI excel vs struggle?**\n\nStudents explore the strengths and weaknesses of AI by comparing AI-generated responses with human responses for different tasks. They learn what AI hallucinations are and how to be critical of AI-generated output. Through hands-on activities, discussions, and real-world applications, students assess AI’s reliability and determine when human oversight is necessary. By the end of the lesson, students justify when AI should or shouldn’t be used in various professional contexts, developing a critical mindset toward AI’s role as a collaborator.",
        "student_overview": "**Where does AI excel vs struggle?**\n\nExplore how AI thinks by comparing its responses to human responses. Through hands-on activities and real-world examples, learn to spot AI hallucinations, assess AI’s reliability, and decide when human oversight is needed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-6",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-7",
      "name": "Uncovering Contradictions",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Can AI contradict itself?**\n\nStudents will be asked to explore the reasons why AI might provide contradictory answers. They will practice refining prompts in order to both induce and eliminate contradictions in AI-generated responses. Additionally, they will examine ways in which AI contradictions can have real-world effects.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Examine AI Contradictions activity guide (one for each pair of students)",
        "student_overview": "**Can AI contradict itself?**\n\nThere are times when even the most sophisticated AI can provide two or more answers that seemingly contradict. In this scenario, it is important to know why this might occur and to employ a handful of strategies to help overcome it. This lesson will provide you the tools to refine prompts in order to reduce or eliminate contradictory responses."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-7",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-8",
      "name": "Understanding Bias",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What is AI bias, and how does it emerge?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how AI bias emerges from biased training data. Students analyze results from online search engines and AI Chat to examine them for bias. In the main activity, students select candidates for a particular job by filtering resumes. They compare their selections with those made by AI and note any bias in the selection process. Throughout the lesson, students brainstorm and discuss strategies to make AI systems more fair and ethical.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the AI Audit activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**What is AI bias, and how does it emerge?**\n\nExplore how AI bias emerges from training data by analyzing search results, evaluating AI-generated decisions, and comparing your own hiring choices with those made by AI. Then, discuss ways to make AI fairer and less biased."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-8",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-9",
      "name": "AI's Wild Imagination",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are some examples of AI hallucinations? What are their impacts?**\n\nThis lesson explores the real-world impacts of AI hallucinations. Building on their previous understanding of AI errors, students analyze real-world case studies where AI misinformation has caused harm. Through discussion, case studies, and fact-checking strategies, students evaluate AI’s reliability and consider its ethical implications in fields like law, healthcare, and journalism.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Hallucination Case Studies activity guide (one per student)\n- Print copies of the Jigsaw Articles (one copy group of four students)",
        "student_overview": "**What are some examples of AI hallucinations? What are their impacts?**\n\nAI can generate false information that has real consequences. In this lesson, you explore examples of AI hallucinations in the real world and practice fact-checking strategies to determine when AI’s responses can and cannot be trusted."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-9",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-10",
      "name": "Debugging and Refining Outputs",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**Can we improve AI's responses?**\n\nStudents explore how to improve AI-generated responses by refining their prompts using a five-step framework: task, context, reference, format, and tone. Through hands-on exploration in AI Chat levels, they test different prompt modifications, analyze how AI responds to varying levels of detail, and apply debugging techniques to enhance accuracy. At the end of the lesson, students summarize their learning about AI prompt refinement by adding ideas to a classroom Anchor Chart.",
        "preparation": "- Prepare a classroom anchor chart containing five columns - Task, Context, Format, Reference, and Tone.",
        "student_overview": "**Can we improve AI's responses?**\n\nRefine AI-generated responses by experimenting with prompt modifications using a five-step framework—task, context, reference, format, and tone—analyzing AI interactions, applying debugging techniques, and summarizing their insights on a classroom Anchor Chart."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-10",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-11",
      "name": "AI as a Co-Creator",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can AI enhance creativity?**\n\nIn this lesson, students take on creative roles to design and launch a product or app that helps students succeed in school. Working in teams, they collaborate with AI across four stages—research, brainstorming, content generation, and editing—to co-create campaign materials like slogans, scripts, and visuals. The activity emphasizes decomposition, prompting strategy, and human-AI collaboration, helping students develop both technical and creative problem-solving skills.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Collaborate on a Product Launch activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can AI enhance creativity?**\n\nIn this lesson, you’ll work with a team to help launch a brand-new product or app for students. You’ll use AI to research, brainstorm, and build your part of the campaign—like coming up with a name, writing a script, or designing a logo. You’ll learn how to guide the AI, improve its responses, and use your own creativity to make something original."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-11",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-12",
      "name": "Remixing, Creativity, and Originality",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do human strengths and AI capabilities interact?**\n\nThis lesson explores how AI can support human creativity through a hands-on remixing challenge. Students interact with AI to refine both their own creative content and AI-generated work, comparing the role of human input in both processes. The lesson emphasizes that while AI can enhance creative work, human judgment is essential for originality, nuance, and meaning.",
        "preparation": "- Prepare copies of the AI Remix Challenge activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How do human strengths and AI capabilities interact?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore how AI can support creativity by remixing and refining content. You compare your ideas with AI’s suggestions and decide what makes something truly creative."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-12",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-13",
      "name": "Ownership, Ethics, and Creativity",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are the ethical considerations of AI collaboration?**\n\nStudents explore ethical and legal questions around ownership, fairness, and transparency when collaborating with AI in creative contexts. Through an interactive spectrum warm-up, real-world case study discussions, and a group policy-writing challenge, students examine how AI-generated content affects artists, musicians, and other creators. They reflect on questions of consent, attribution, and compensation, then draft policies that balance the benefits of AI with the rights of original creators. This lesson builds students’ ability to evaluate AI as a collaborator and justify when AI should or shouldn’t be used, especially in ethically complex situations.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Create a Copyright Policy activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**What are the ethical considerations of AI collaboration?**\n\nWhen AI creates things like art, music, or writing, who should get credit? In this lesson, you explore real cases where AI-generated content raised tough questions. You work with your group to write a policy for how AI companies should treat creative work, and reflect on how to balance innovation with fairness to human creators."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-13",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-14",
      "name": "AI's Role in Society",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How should AI be used in solving real-world problems?**\n\nStudents choose a real-world example of AI in use within the community, investigating who might benefit and who might be harmed from its implementation. They use their research to draft a call to action in which they propose solutions to the perceived issues that they uncover.",
        "student_overview": "**How should AI be used in solving real-world problems?**\n\nYou explore a variety of different ways that AI is being and will be used within your community. Using a chatbot to summarize a variety of different articles, you create your own draft of a short-form video script that addresses issues that you have uncovered."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-14",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-15",
      "name": "AI Time Capsule Project",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "In this project, students work with AI to develop a future prediction and create a presentation that explains their process. They collaborate with AI to generate and refine ideas, evaluate outputs for accuracy and bias, and reflect on how they shaped the final prediction. The project centers on ethical reasoning, student voice, and thoughtful use of multimodal inputs to support transparency and agency in AI collaboration.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the AI Time Capsule Project Planning Guide (one per student)",
        "student_overview": "In this project, you work with AI to make and refine a prediction about the future. Then, you create a presentation that explains how you used AI, what decisions you made, and how you improved the prediction to make it more realistic, fair, and your own."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "lesson-15",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-4",
        "script.name": "pswai-pilot-2024"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "lesson-3",
